      Everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20

You   know the   drill. A public company does a bad thing. When the bad thi=
ng becomes public, the company=E2=80=99s stock goes down. Shareholders sue =
the company for securities fraud. The lawsuits are always the same: =E2=80=
=9CYou told us in your public filings that you were=C2=A0not=C2=A0doing a b=
ad thing, so we bought your stock. But you were lying, and when the world f=
ound out you were doing the bad thing, the stock went down and we lost mone=
y. We were defrauded out of our money by your lies.=E2=80=9D Everything bad=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0polluting,   sexual harassment,  animal abuse,=C2=A0making =
a buggy video game,   social media companies failing to safeguard user priv=
acy,   social media companies having a negative effect on society,=C2=A0lax=
 information security practices leading to data breaches=C2=A0=E2=80=94 can=
 also be characterized as securities fraud, if a public company does it.
Twitter Inc. is a public company. Last month its former head of information=
 security, Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko,  publicized a whistle-blow=
er complaint saying that Twitter did bad information-security and user-priv=
acy things. If Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations are true, then under standard ev=
erything-is-securities-fraud=C2=A0theory, they are securities fraud. (On th=
at theory, Zatko filed his whistle-blower complaint with the Securities and=
 Exchange Commission.)=C2=A0And in fact Twitter=E2=80=99s stock was down ab=
out 7.3% =E2=80=94=C2=A0$3.15 per share, or about $2.4 billion of market ca=
pitalization =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the day that Zatko went public. And so of co=
urse   the inevitable happened:

Twitter Inc. executives should be held accountable for concealing operation=
al problems at the popular social-media platform and firing a whistle-blowe=
r who sought to address the issues, according to an investor=E2=80=99s laws=
uit.=C2=A0
Jack Dorsey, Twitter=E2=80=99s co-founder, Chief Executive Officer Parag Ag=
rawal and other managers violated federal securities laws by making false s=
tatements about the operational miscues to bolster the platform=E2=80=99s s=
tock price, shareholder William Baker said in a federal suit filed Tuesday =
in California. ...
The suit seeks class-action status on behalf of all Twitter shareholders wh=
o owned the stock over a two-year period starting in 2020. In his complaint=
, Baker argues the disclosure last month of Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations sen=
t Twitter shares down as much as 7%, =E2=80=9Cdamaging investors.=E2=80=9D

Yep yep yep yep yep. Here is  the complaint, which is as standard as can be=
.
Now. The theory of everything-is-securities-fraud is something like: If a c=
ompany does a bad thing, that will be bad for its business in some way. It =
will lose customers or lose employees or pay fines or whatever. This will r=
educe the profits available to shareholders, which will reduce the value of=
 the stock. If shareholders had known about the bad thing, they could have =
properly valued the company; the fact that the bad thing was hidden prevent=
ed that and inflated the stock price. When it came out, the stock fell to i=
ts true value, and the deceived shareholders lost money. Byrne Hobart  once=
 wrote:
This is =E2=80=A6 partly a result of how efficiently markets aggregate and =
share information: it's hard to directly measure the effect of corporate ma=
lfeasance on sales or employee retention, especially over long periods. But=
 stock prices react fast, and they represent a guess about the long term. S=
o if you want to know exactly how bad some piece of news was, the only way =
to rephrase that is "how bad was it for shareholders?=E2=80=9D
And so you might tell a story about Twitter that is like: =E2=80=9CIf Zatko=
=E2=80=99s allegations are true, it might lose customers or pay fines or ha=
ve to spend more on security, so its long-term value is lower by about $2.4=
 billion, which is why the stock went down and shareholders lost money.=E2=
=80=9D And in fact that is the story that the complaint here tells:
The statements contained in [Twitter=E2=80=99s filings] were materially fal=
se and/or misleading because they misrepresented and failed to disclose the=
 following adverse facts pertaining to the Company=E2=80=99s business, oper=
ations and prospects, which were known to Defendants or recklessly disregar=
ded by them. Specifically, Defendants made false and/or misleading statemen=
ts and/or failed to disclose that: (1) Twitter knew about security concerns=
 on their platform; (2) Twitter actively worked to hide the security concer=
ns from the board, the investing public, and regulators; (3) contrary to re=
presentations in SEC filings, Twitter did not take steps to improve securit=
y; (4) Twitter=E2=80=99s active refusal to address security issues increase=
d the risk of loss of public goodwill; and (5) as a result, Defendants=E2=
=80=99 statements about Twitter=E2=80=99s business, operations, and prospec=
ts, were materially false and misleading and/or lacked a reasonable basis a=
t all relevant times.
The standard story: Because the bad things were concealed, Twitter=E2=80=99=
s shareholders had a false picture of its business, operations and prospect=
s.
Except that that is not a very realistic story about Twitter, because Twitt=
er has a pending merger agreement to be acquired for cash by Elon Musk at $=
54.20 per share, a deal that shareholders  overwhelmingly approved this wee=
k. The long-term value of Twitter, to its shareholders, is a flat=C2=A0$54.=
20 per share, if Musk ends up closing the deal that he signed in April. If =
he=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0close the deal then sure, sure, Twitter is wor=
th some uncertain series of cash flows, and those cash flows might be lower=
 due to fines or lost users or whatever. And he is=C2=A0trying=C2=A0to get =
out of the deal, and the Zatko allegations give him   some additional excus=
es for getting out of it. But the odds of him being forced to close at $54.=
20 still seem fairly high.
If Musk closed the deal tomorrow, then Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders would=
 get $54.20 per share, and all the Zatko stuff wouldn=E2=80=99t matter.
  [2]
=C2=A0It would matter=C2=A0to Musk:=C2=A0If Twitter pays big fines or loses=
 users due to Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations then Musk, as the sole post-merge=
r shareholder,
  [3]
 will lose money. But to Twitter=E2=80=99s existing public shareholders (ot=
her than Musk), Twitter simply is not a long-term value proposition. It=E2=
=80=99s a receipt for $54.20 in cash, with some dispute about whether Musk =
has to pay.=C2=A0
And, similarly, the reason Twitter=E2=80=99s stock fell by 7.3% when Zatko=
=E2=80=99s allegations came out is not primarily that shareholders evaluate=
d those allegations and said =E2=80=9Cooh, this is going to cost Twitter ab=
out $2.4 billion in fines and lost business=E2=80=9D and the stock fell to =
reflect that. The reason it fell that day is that shareholders evaluated th=
ose allegations and said =E2=80=9Cooh, this gives Musk some more excuses to=
 get out of the deal.=E2=80=9D If Musk closes, Twitter is worth $54.20. If =
he doesn=E2=80=99t close, it=E2=80=99s worth much less. The Zatko allegatio=
ns probably somewhat decrease the value of Twitter in a world in which the =
Musk deal falls through, but their main effect is surely to increase the=C2=
=A0probability=C2=A0of that outcome.
This leads to weird results. For instance, surely the securities-fraud case=
 will be litigated and decided  long after Twitter=E2=80=99s litigation wit=
h Musk is over. If Musk wins and gets out of the deal, then (1) presumably =
the securities-fraud case will go forward, (2) it will be a pretty standard=
 everything-is-securities-fraud case, and (3) it will have potentially enor=
mous damages, if Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint is the difference between Twitte=
r getting $54.20 per share from Musk and being worth=C2=A0$20 or $25 or wha=
tever without him.
If=C2=A0Musk loses and has to close at $54.20, then it is a little hard to =
argue that shareholders were damaged by the Zatko stuff: The stock was wort=
h $54.20 before the complaint came out and $54.20 afterwards. But it is not=
 impossible=C2=A0to argue that. The argument is that the Zatko revelations =
reduced the probability=C2=A0of the deal closing, even though it ultimately=
 closed; shareholders were deceived into buying stock at one price assuming=
 a high probability of closing, and when the truth came out the probability=
 dropped and they lost money, at least temporarily.
  [4]
=C2=A0This strikes me as a fine argument in theory though a little nit-pick=
y to actually make in court. Also at this point you are trying to get the m=
oney out of=C2=A0Musk, who owns Twitter in this scenario and who had nothin=
g to do with any of the alleged bad things; that seems a little unfair.
  [5]

If Musk and Twitter renegotiate the deal and he ends up paying, you know, $=
49.95 per share, then I suppose the securities-fraud case goes forward and =
they argue =E2=80=9Cthe Zatko allegations are what caused that price drop.=
=E2=80=9D Again you are effectively suing Musk for the money in this scenar=
io.
Meanwhile Musk is still litigating his own case, and he is still   looking =
for reasons to get out of the deal. He has already used Zatko=E2=80=99s all=
egations (about bad information security practices etc.) as an excuse to te=
rminate the deal, and he has used Zatko=E2=80=99s severance package from Tw=
itter as a separate excuse to terminate the deal. Is this=C2=A0lawsuit=C2=
=A0yet another excuse? Meh, I mean, probably not =E2=80=94=C2=A0it seems un=
likely that the lawsuit would have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=
=9D on Twitter, which is what would give him an=C2=A0out =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 if it has some non-zero chance of success maybe he=E2=80=99ll throw it on =
the pile.
What if it works? What if Musk gets out of the deal because shareholders su=
ed for fraud, and him getting out of the deal is what gives them a case for=
 fraud? =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s so recursive,=E2=80=9D  tweeted law professor=
 Ann Lipton; =E2=80=9Cthe mere fact of the lawsuit makes people worry the d=
eal won=E2=80=99t go through, and that makes the stock price fall more, whi=
ch increases the potential damages.=E2=80=9D

