   =20
      People are worried about stock buybacks
   =20
 =20

I take a very simple view of stock buybacks:
=09People give a company money to do stuff.=09The company does stuff with t=
he money.=09The stuff that the company does makes money.=09The company give=
s the money it makes in step 3 back to the people who gave it money in step=
 1.

People   like to overcomplicate this. =E2=80=9CCompanies should not give mo=
ney back to shareholders,=E2=80=9D they say;=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthey should inve=
st it in new factories and growth and innovation.=E2=80=9D Yes fine often t=
hat is true, agreed. But at some level it cannot be=C2=A0perpetually ruled =
out=C2=A0that the people who give companies money to do things can=C2=A0nev=
er get their money back. Why would you invest money in a company if it coul=
d never give you any money back?
This is oversimplified, of course, and you could have quibbles. =E2=80=9CTh=
e company can pay you a dividend, but it cannot ever buy back stock=E2=80=
=9D seems to be a view that some people have.=C2=A0I find it a little baffl=
ing but, fine, whatever, that=E2=80=99s a way for the company to pay people=
 for providing capital; it can work. One practical reason that you might ha=
ve this view, in the US in 2022, is that stock buybacks are much more=C2=A0=
tax-efficient=C2=A0than dividends. When a company pays a dividend, all its =
shareholders pay tax on the entire amount of the dividend. When a company s=
pends the same amount of money buying back stock, most shareholders don=E2=
=80=99t pay taxes (because they don=E2=80=99t sell any stock), and the ones=
 who do only pay taxes on their=C2=A0gain=C2=A0(the difference between what=
 they paid for the stock and the buyback price). When I was an investment=
=C2=A0banker pitching share-repurchase strategies, this was a good argument=
 for doing a stock buyback instead of a dividend. But if you are suspicious=
 of stock buybacks, this is a bad thing: This is just =E2=80=9Cstock buybac=
ks let companies pay money to shareholders without making them pay tax.=E2=
=80=9D You might want them to pay tax!
And so the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022  imposes a 1% excise tax on stoc=
k buybacks by public companies. The people who demanded that tax probably d=
islike stock buybacks a lot more than I do, so in some theoretical sense I =
feel like I should disapprove of this tax. But on the other hand the excise=
 tax just makes stock buybacks=C2=A0slightly=C2=A0less tax efficient, putti=
ng them on closer to a level playing field with dividends, and I guess that=
=E2=80=99s fine. I can=E2=80=99t get too worked up about it.
That said there are some oddities. At Axios,  Dan Primack reports=C2=A0that=
 the 1% tax =E2=80=9Ccould be applied to SPAC redemptions.=E2=80=9D The way=
 a special purpose acquisition company works is:
=09A sponsor raises money by selling stock to the public at $10 per share.=
=09She puts the money in a pot and looks for an acquisition target.=09If sh=
e finds one, the SPAC merges with the target. The target gets the money in =
the pot and becomes a public company; the shareholders of the SPAC get shar=
es of the target.
  [6]

=09If she does not find a target (or the shareholders don=E2=80=99t approve=
 the one she finds), which seems increasingly likely for a lot of SPACs the=
se days, then the SPAC liquidates and returns the money in the pot (plus a =
bit of interest) to shareholders.

Is that a =E2=80=9Cstock buyback=E2=80=9D? Well, sure, I guess. People put =
money into the company, time passed, and the company gave them the money ba=
ck. The company tried to do something with the money, but it failed, so it =
just returned it. And there=E2=80=99s a 1% tax on the way out.

