      Meme-stock IR
   =20
 =20

RCI Hospitality Holdings Inc. (ticker: RICK) is a US publicly traded compan=
y that operates =E2=80=9C adult entertainment nightclubs=E2=80=9D under nam=
es like Rick=E2=80=99s Cabaret, Scarlett=E2=80=99s Cabaret, Temptations Adu=
lt Cabaret, Foxy=E2=80=99s Cabaret, Kappa Men=E2=80=99s Club, etc. We have =
  talked about RCI previously=C2=A0because this year it was trying =E2=80=
=9Cto generate buzz among retail traders and boost its slumping stock price=
=E2=80=9D by doing meme-stock stuff like taking retail questions on earning=
s calls, talking about non-fungible tokens, etc.
  [7]

Yesterday its chief financial officer, Bradley Chhay, disclosed that he=C2=
=A0sold 69 shares of RCI stock at a price of $69.69 per share. As a person =
who writes on the internet, I believe that I am professionally obligated to=
 say: nice. Sixty-nine is the internet sex number.
Chhay cleared about $4,800 on the sales; he has about 3,500 shares left (wo=
rth about $250,000) and  gets paid about $500,000 per year. It is possible =
that these stock sales were to pay for a kitchen renovation or whatever, bu=
t my assumption is that he thought it would be funny to sell 69 shares at $=
69.69, so he did. Presumably he used a limit order. =E2=80=9CIf this stock =
hits $69.69, you know what to do,=E2=80=9D he told his broker. (=E2=80=9CNi=
ce,=E2=80=9D the broker replied.)=C2=A0If you are the CFO of a publicly tra=
ded strip-club company and you sell 69 shares of stock at $69.69 then I gue=
ss retail investors will say =E2=80=9Cthat guy is cool=E2=80=9D and buy=C2=
=A0your stock. (Also, uh, I guess I will write about it?)=C2=A0This is how =
capital markets work now, I=E2=80=99m sorry.

