  [1] The simplest and dumbest valuation technique is that you look at the =
price/earnings ratio of the Standard & Poor=E2=80=99s 500 index =E2=80=94 c=
urrently about 19.2 =E2=80=94 and multiply the annual earnings by that, imp=
lying about a $1.92 billion valuation for a $100-million-a-year company. Pa=
tagonia=E2=80=99s profits are =E2=80=9Csome $100 million a year=E2=80=9D an=
d it is =E2=80=9Cvalued at about $3 billion,=E2=80=9D so, right order of ma=
gnitude.


  [2] You could hypothetically imagine a story in which the Zatko stuff bro=
ught down the purchase price and thus gave shareholders a fraud claim. This=
 would be something like: =E2=80=9CYou told us that the company wasn=E2=80=
=99t doing bad things, so we valued it at $45, which attributed some value =
to the possibility of a takeover at a very high premium. But the company *w=
as* doing bad things, which we didn=E2=80=99t know, but which potential acq=
uirers did, so there was no takeover at $60 and you ended up selling cheape=
r than we expected.=E2=80=9D This story has problems =E2=80=94 $54.20 is a =
significant premium to Twitter=E2=80=99s pre-deal stock price, so it is har=
d to articulate exactly how you were deceived =E2=80=94 but the main one is=
 that Musk *didn=E2=80=99t* know about Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations when he =
negotiated the deal price. So those allegations did not bring down the valu=
e that Twitter (hopes it has) achieved for shareholders.


  [3] I say that for simplicity, but in fact Musk signed up equity co-inves=
tors on his deal to buy Twitter. It has been a *long* time since anyone men=
tioned them, and it=E2=80=99s not clear at this point that they=E2=80=99ll =
actually put up money if he is forced to close, but in theory if he closes =
he=E2=80=99ll be Twitter=E2=80=99s majority shareholder but there will be o=
ther shareholders including Kingdom Holding Co., Qatar Holdings, Andreessen=
 Horowitz, Fidelity and Binance.


  [4] This is a bit analogous to suing a *bond* issuer for lying about its =
finances, even if the bonds were ultimately paid back. If you knew the trut=
h about the issuer=E2=80=99s finances, you would have thought its credit wa=
s worse and demanded a higher interest rate. But you didn=E2=80=99t know th=
e truth, so you bought the bonds at a relatively low interest rate. But the=
n the risks that you didn=E2=80=99t know about didn=E2=80=99t lead to defau=
lt, so you got your money back anyway.


  [5] The lawsuit names Twitter, Jack Dorsey, Ned Segal and Parag Agrawal a=
s defendants, but in practice the money to settle it is going to come from =
Twitter (or its insurer).


  [6] Or they can redeem for cash but I will ignore that here for simplicit=
y. In practice if they redeem for cash that should raise similar 1% tax iss=
ues.


  [7] We actually   talked about it once before, in 2017, because Martin Sh=
kreli once ran a hedge fund that put all of its money in RCI stock. Sure.


