<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Patagonia</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you own a business and it is a big successf=
ul business and makes a lot of money, you will end up getting a lot of mone=
y. If you do not want a lot of money (because you find it embarrassing to b=
e rich, etc.), or if you want to give money to good causes rather than spen=
ding it on yachts, you can get your check =E2=80=94=C2=A0a dividend or prof=
it share or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0from the company each quarter, and then=
 hand the money over to charity. But there are some problems:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Getting $100 million a year from your=
 company and donating=C2=A0$100 million a year to charity is not necessaril=
y all that tax-efficient. For instance, charitable donations can be deducte=
d from your taxable income, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9wdWJsaWNhdGlvbnMvc=
DUyNiM6fjp0ZXh0PVlvdXIlMjBkZWR1Y3Rpb24lMjBmb3IlMjBjaGFyaXRhYmxlJTIwY29udHJp=
YnV0aW9ucyxvciUyMDUwJTI1JTIwbGltaXRzJTIwbWF5JTIwYXBwbHkuJnRleHQ9VGhlJTIwNjA=
lMjUlMjBsaW1pdCUyMGlzJTIwc3VzcGVuZGVkJTIwZm9yJTIwY2VydGFpbiUyMGNhc2glMjBjb2=
50cmlidXRpb25zLg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4afc6d44" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">there are limit=
s</a> to how much they can reduce that income. If you get $100 million and =
donate $100 million then you have nothing left over, but you might still ow=
e $10 million of taxes.=C2=A0If the money is coming from your company and g=
oing to charity, it might not be ideal for it to make an intermediate stop =
on your personal tax return. There are frictions.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you die, your heirs will get the company, which me=
ans they will start getting those checks, and maybe=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em=
>will start spending the money on yachts instead of charity. You might want=
 to prevent this and keep the money running from the company to charity for=
ever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This is sort of a stupid met=
aphysical point, but if you own 100% of a <em>company </em>that pays you $1=
00 million per year, then you are technically a =E2=80=9Cbillionaire.=E2=80=
=9D This is true even if you get the $100 million each year and give it awa=
y immediately, leaving you with=C2=A0no cash at all. The=C2=A0<em>company=
=C2=A0</em>is an asset, and traditional valuation techniques will tell you =
that a company that makes a profit of $100 million a year is worth, you kno=
w, $2 billion or $3 billion, something like that.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Bankers will occasionally show up at your office pitching a deal =
to sell your company for billions of dollars, because that=E2=80=99s what i=
t=E2=80=99s worth. So even if you give away all the=C2=A0<em>money</em>, yo=
u continue to own an asset worth billions of dollars, making you a billiona=
ire. We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062=
030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEt=
MDctMjIvcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybS1nb3QtcmljaC1tYWtpbmctcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHk=
tZmlybXMtcmljaD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTE1MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA5MTUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf702b8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about this befor=
e</a>, in the context of people who would like to be billionaires =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0there are some bragging rights =E2=80=94=C2=A0and who incorporate and=
 sell stakes in their businesses in order to formalize that status. But if =
you=E2=80=99re a person who finds it embarrassing to be rich, owning a mult=
ibillion-dollar asset is embarrassing.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8w=
OS8xNC9jbGltYXRlL3BhdGFnb25pYS1jbGltYXRlLXBoaWxhbnRocm9weS1jaG91aW5hcmQuaHR=
tbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5d2093e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a straightforward solution</=
a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A half century after founding the outdoor appa=
rel maker Patagonia, Yvon Chouinard, the eccentric rock climber who became =
a reluctant billionaire with his unconventional spin on capitalism, has giv=
en the company away.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rather than selling the company or taking it p=
ublic, Mr. Chouinard, his wife and two adult children have transferred thei=
r ownership of Patagonia, valued at about $3 billion, to a specially design=
ed trust and a nonprofit organization. They were created to preserve the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s independence and ensure that all of its profits =E2=80=94 s=
ome $100 million a year =E2=80=94 are used to combat climate change and pro=
tect undeveloped land around the globe. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Patagonia will continue to operate as a privat=
e, for-profit corporation based in Ventura, Calif., selling more than $1 bi=
llion worth of jackets, hats and ski pants each year. But the Chouinards, w=
ho controlled Patagonia until last month, no longer own the company.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But they still=C2=A0<em>control=C2=A0</em>it, =
more or less:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In August, the family irrevocably transferred =
all the company=E2=80=99s voting stock, equivalent to 2 percent of the over=
all shares, into a newly established entity known as the Patagonia Purpose =
Trust.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trust, which will be overseen by members o=
f the family and their closest advisers, is intended to ensure that Patagon=
ia makes good on its commitment to run a socially responsible business and =
give away its profits. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The Chouinards then donated the other=
 98 percent of Patagonia, its common shares, to a newly established nonprof=
it organization called the Holdfast Collective, which will now be the recip=
ient of all the company=E2=80=99s profits and use the funds to combat clima=
te change. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t respect the stock mar=
ket at all,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9COnce you=E2=80=99re public, you=E2=
=80=99ve lost control over the company, and you have to maximize profits fo=
r the shareholder, and then you become one of these irresponsible companies=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead of the control being in the hands of t=
he family,=C2=A0it is in the hands of a trust controlled by the family. For=
 now those are close to the same thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0Yvon Chouinard just t=
ells the company what to do =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in expectation, 100 years fr=
om now, those things will probably produce different outcomes. The way you =
pick your successors at a Purpose Trust is probably different from how you =
pick your heirs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And instead of the profits going to the family=
, which then donates them to a nonprofit, they go directly to the nonprofit=
. Which is tax-efficient and, again, removes the possibility of future heir=
s redirecting the profits to their own yachts. Also it allows Chouinard to =
say that he =E2=80=9Cno longer owns the company=E2=80=9D and have a New Yor=
k Times headline saying =E2=80=9CBillionaire No More,=E2=80=9D which seems =
to have been an important goal:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI was in Forbes magazine =
listed as a billionaire, which really, really pissed me off,=E2=80=9D he sa=
id. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t have $1 billion in the bank. I don=E2=80=99t d=
rive Lexuses.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, he didn=E2=80=99t have $1 billion in th=
e bank; he had stock in a corporation worth $3 billion. Now he technically =
does not.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me mostly as a fairly simple bit =
of financial planning to achieve an unusual but understandable set of goals=
. (Stop owning a company without letting anyone else own it, turn a for-pro=
fit company into a vehicle for philanthropy without some of the restriction=
s of becoming a nonprofit company, avoid flowing corporate-to-charity money=
 through personal income.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, though, it is an interesting form of cor=
porate governance. The ordinary rule is that a company is owned by its shar=
eholders, and the shareholders have a claim on its profits, and the shareho=
lders have ultimate authority to hire and fire the company=E2=80=99s board =
and managers. In public companies with dispersed anonymous shareholders, th=
e board and managers mostly run the company without too much shareholder in=
terference, and they assume that the shareholders just want them to maximiz=
e profits. In companies with controlling shareholders, the controlling shar=
eholders tend to have real authority over the managers, and can tell them w=
hat they want to maximize, which may or may not be profits. (In public comp=
anies with lots of environmental, social and governance-minded investors, t=
he ESG investors can also lobby the managers to maximize something other th=
an profits.) The shareholders=E2=80=99 residual claim on the company=E2=80=
=99s profits and their ability to tell the managers what to do are related,=
 but they don=E2=80=99t absolutely=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>to go together. =
The shareholders could come to the managers and say =E2=80=9Cas shareholder=
s, we control the company, and we instruct you to stop giving us the profit=
s and start giving them to charity instead.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s more or=
 less what happened here.</p>
