<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Twitter Inc. is a public company. Last month i=
ts former head of information security, Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatk=
o, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY29tL3RlY2hub2xvZ3kvaW50ZXJhY3RpdmUvMj=
AyMi90d2l0dGVyLXdoaXN0bGVibG93ZXItc2VjLXNwYW0vP2l0aWQ9aHAtdG9wLXRhYmxlLW1ha=
W4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB02c69d46" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> publicized a whistle-blower =
complaint</a> saying that Twitter did bad information-security and user-pri=
vacy things. If Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations are true, then under standard e=
verything-is-securities-fraud=C2=A0theory, they are securities fraud. (On t=
hat theory, Zatko filed his whistle-blower complaint with the Securities an=
d Exchange Commission.)=C2=A0And in fact Twitter=E2=80=99s stock was down a=
bout 7.3% =E2=80=94=C2=A0$3.15 per share, or about $2.4 billion of market c=
apitalization =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the day that Zatko went public. And so of c=
ourse <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270=
537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMTQvdHd=
pdHRlci1oaWQtc2VjdXJpdHktaXNzdWVzLXRvLWJvb3N0LXN0b2NrLWludmVzdG9yLXN1aXQtc2=
F5cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTE1MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA5MTUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfcad13d6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the inevitable happened</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Twitter Inc. executives should be held account=
able for concealing operational problems at the popular social-media platfo=
rm and firing a whistle-blower who sought to address the issues, according =
to an investor=E2=80=99s lawsuit.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jack Dorsey, Twitter=E2=80=99s co-founder, Chi=
ef Executive Officer Parag Agrawal and other managers violated federal secu=
rities laws by making false statements about the operational miscues to bol=
ster the platform=E2=80=99s stock price, shareholder William Baker said in =
a federal suit filed Tuesday in California. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The suit seeks class-action status on behalf o=
f all Twitter shareholders who owned the stock over a two-year period start=
ing in 2020. In his complaint, Baker argues the disclosure last month of Za=
tko=E2=80=99s allegations sent Twitter shares down as much as 7%, =E2=80=9C=
damaging investors.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yep yep yep yep yep. Here is <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHM=
uYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JaV1pPUXU1Lm8wWS92MA/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB097de9fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the complaint</a>, which is as sta=
ndard as can be.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now. The theory of everything-is-securities-fr=
aud is something like: If a company does a bad thing, that will be bad for =
its business in some way. It will lose customers or lose employees or pay f=
ines or whatever. This will reduce the profits available to shareholders, w=
hich will reduce the value of the stock. If shareholders had known about th=
e bad thing, they could have properly valued the company; the fact that the=
 bad thing was hidden prevented that and inflated the stock price. When it =
came out, the stock fell to its true value, and the deceived shareholders l=
ost money. Byrne Hobart <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZGlmZi5jby9wL2FkdmVydGlzaW5nLWFuZ=
C1zdHJhdGVnaWMtY29uc3VsdGluZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf3946f9b" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 once wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is =E2=80=A6 partly a result =
of how efficiently markets aggregate and share information: it's hard to di=
rectly measure the effect of corporate malfeasance on sales or employee ret=
ention, especially over long periods. But stock prices react fast, and they=
 represent a guess about the long term. So if you want to know exactly how =
bad some piece of news was, the only way to rephrase that is "how bad was i=
t for shareholders?=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you might tell a story about Twitter th=
at is like: =E2=80=9CIf Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations are true, it might lose=
 customers or pay fines or have to spend more on security, so its long-term=
 value is lower by about $2.4 billion, which is why the stock went down and=
 shareholders lost money.=E2=80=9D And in fact that is the story that the c=
omplaint here tells:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The statements contained in [Twitt=
er=E2=80=99s filings] were materially false and/or misleading because they =
misrepresented and failed to disclose the following adverse facts pertainin=
g to the Company=E2=80=99s business, operations and prospects, which were k=
nown to Defendants or recklessly disregarded by them. Specifically, Defenda=
nts made false and/or misleading statements and/or failed to disclose that:=
 (1) Twitter knew about security concerns on their platform; (2) Twitter ac=
tively worked to hide the security concerns from the board, the investing p=
ublic, and regulators; (3) contrary to representations in SEC filings, Twit=
ter did not take steps to improve security; (4) Twitter=E2=80=99s active re=
fusal to address security issues increased the risk of loss of public goodw=
ill; and (5) as a result, Defendants=E2=80=99 statements about Twitter=E2=
=80=99s business, operations, and prospects, were materially false and misl=
eading and/or lacked a reasonable basis at all relevant times.</p></blockqu=
ote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The standard story: Because the bad things wer=
e concealed, Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders had a false picture of its busi=
ness, operations and prospects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except that that is not a very realistic story=
 about Twitter, because Twitter has a pending merger agreement to be acquir=
ed for cash by Elon Musk at $54.20 per share, a deal that shareholders <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMDAwMTQxODA5MS8wM=
DAxMTkzMTI1MjIyNDQyODkvZDQwMzMwNmQ4ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa942322=
d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> overwhelmingly approved</a> this week. The long-term value of=
 Twitter, to its shareholders, is a flat=C2=A0$54.20 per share, if Musk end=
s up closing the deal that he signed in April. If he=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=
=99t</em>=C2=A0close the deal then sure, sure, Twitter is worth some uncert=
ain series of cash flows, and those cash flows might be lower due to fines =
or lost users or whatever. And he is=C2=A0<em>trying=C2=A0</em>to get out o=
f the deal, and the Zatko allegations give him <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMzAvbXVzay1jYW5jZWxzLXR3aXR0ZXItZGVhb=
C1zb21lLW1vcmU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1=
dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN=
0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB79553c91" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  some additional excuse=
s</a> for getting out of it. But the odds of him being forced to close at $=
54.20 still seem fairly high.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Musk closed the deal tomorrow, then Twitter=
=E2=80=99s shareholders would get $54.20 per share, and all the Zatko stuff=
 wouldn=E2=80=99t matter.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It would matter=C2=A0<em>to Musk</em>:=C2=A0If Twitter pays big f=
ines or loses users due to Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations then Musk, as the so=
le post-merger shareholder,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> will lose money. But to Twitter=E2=80=99s existing public shareholders=
 (other than Musk), Twitter simply is not a long-term value proposition. It=
=E2=80=99s a receipt for $54.20 in cash, with some dispute about whether Mu=
sk has to pay.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, similarly, the reason Twitter=E2=80=99s s=
tock fell by 7.3% when Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations came out is not primaril=
y that shareholders evaluated those allegations and said =E2=80=9Cooh, this=
 is going to cost Twitter about $2.4 billion in fines and lost business=E2=
=80=9D and the stock fell to reflect that. The reason it fell that day is t=
hat shareholders evaluated those allegations and said =E2=80=9Cooh, this gi=
ves Musk some more excuses to get out of the deal.=E2=80=9D If Musk closes,=
 Twitter is worth $54.20. If he doesn=E2=80=99t close, it=E2=80=99s worth m=
uch less. The Zatko allegations probably somewhat decrease the <em>value </=
em>of Twitter in a world in which the Musk deal falls through, but their ma=
in effect is surely to increase the=C2=A0<em>probability=C2=A0</em>of that =
outcome.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This leads to weird results. For instance, sur=
ely the securities-fraud case will be litigated and decided <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0d=
GVyLmNvbS9Bbm5NTGlwdG9uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTcwMTg1NzkwMjM5Njc4NDY0/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB3454b310" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> long after</a> Twitter=E2=80=99s litigation =
with Musk is over. If Musk wins and gets out of the deal, then (1) presumab=
ly the securities-fraud case will go forward, (2) it will be a pretty stand=
ard everything-is-securities-fraud case, and (3) it will have potentially <=
em>enormous </em>damages, if Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint is the difference be=
tween Twitter getting $54.20 per share from Musk and being worth=C2=A0$20 o=
r $25 or whatever without him.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If=C2=A0Musk loses and has to close at $54.20,=
 then it is a little hard to argue that shareholders were damaged by the Za=
tko stuff: The stock was worth $54.20 before the complaint came out and $54=
.20 afterwards. But it is not <em>impossible=C2=A0</em>to argue that. The a=
rgument is that the Zatko revelations reduced the <em>probability=C2=A0</em=
>of the deal closing, even though it ultimately closed; shareholders were d=
eceived into buying stock at one price assuming a high probability of closi=
ng, and when the truth came out the probability dropped and they lost money=
, at least temporarily.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This strikes me as a fine argument in theory though a little nit-=
picky to actually make in court. Also at this point you are trying to get t=
he money out of=C2=A0<em>Musk</em>, who owns Twitter in this scenario and w=
ho had nothing to do with any of the alleged bad things; that seems a littl=
e unfair.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Musk and Twitter renegotiate the deal and h=
e ends up paying, you know, $49.95 per share, then I suppose the securities=
-fraud case goes forward and they argue =E2=80=9Cthe Zatko allegations are =
what caused that price drop.=E2=80=9D Again you are effectively suing Musk =
for the money in this scenario.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile Musk is still litigating his own cas=
e, and he is still <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjItMDktMTIvY2l0aS1nb3QtaXRzLTUwMC1taWxsaW9uLWJhY2s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxNTIyX=
01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rl=
cm09MjIwOTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6f834=
b51" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  looking for reasons</a> to get out of the deal. He has alrea=
dy used Zatko=E2=80=99s allegations (about bad information security practic=
es etc.) as an excuse to terminate the deal, and he has used Zatko=E2=80=99=
s severance package from Twitter as a separate excuse to terminate the deal=
. Is this=C2=A0<em>lawsuit=C2=A0</em>yet another excuse? Meh, I mean, proba=
bly not =E2=80=94=C2=A0it seems unlikely that the lawsuit would have a =E2=
=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter, which is what would give=
 him an=C2=A0out =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if it has some non-zero chance of succe=
ss maybe he=E2=80=99ll throw it on the pile.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if it works? What if Musk gets out of the=
 deal because shareholders sued for fraud, and him getting out of the deal =
is what gives them a case for fraud? =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s so recursive,=E2=
=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.27=
0537/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9Bbm5NTGlwdG9uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTcwMTg4MDUyMTE4Nz=
czNzYx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98ad9f1d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> tweeted law professor A=
nn Lipton</a>; =E2=80=9Cthe mere fact of the lawsuit makes people worry the=
 deal won=E2=80=99t go through, and that makes the stock price fall more, w=
hich increases the potential damages.=E2=80=9D</p>
