<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I take a very simple view of stock buybacks:</=
p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People give a company money to do stu=
ff.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company does stuff with th=
e money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The stuff that the compan=
y does makes money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company gi=
ves the money it makes in step 3 back to the people who gave it money in st=
ep 1.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDctMDkvY29tcGFuaWVzLWtlZXAtYnV5aW5nLWJhY2stc3RvY2s_=
Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5=
ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBc304f088" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  like to overcomplicate this</a>. =E2=80=
=9CCompanies should not give money back to shareholders,=E2=80=9D they say;=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthey should invest it in new factories and growth and innova=
tion.=E2=80=9D Yes fine often that is true, agreed. But at some level it ca=
nnot be=C2=A0<em>perpetually ruled out=C2=A0</em>that the people who give c=
ompanies money to do things can=C2=A0<em>never get their money back</em>. W=
hy would you invest money in a company if it could never give you any money=
 back?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is oversimplified, of course, and you cou=
ld have quibbles. =E2=80=9CThe company can pay you a <em>dividend</em>, but=
 it cannot ever buy back stock=E2=80=9D seems to be a view that some people=
 have.=C2=A0I find it a little baffling but, fine, whatever, that=E2=80=99s=
 a way for the company to pay people for providing capital; it can work. On=
e practical reason that you might have this view, in the US in 2022, is tha=
t stock buybacks are much more=C2=A0<em>tax-efficient=C2=A0</em>than divide=
nds. When a company pays a dividend, all its shareholders pay tax on the en=
tire amount of the dividend. When a company spends the same amount of money=
 buying back stock, most shareholders don=E2=80=99t pay taxes (because they=
 don=E2=80=99t sell any stock), and the ones who do only pay taxes on their=
=C2=A0<em>gain=C2=A0</em>(the difference between what they paid for the sto=
ck and the buyback price). When I was an investment=C2=A0banker pitching sh=
are-repurchase strategies, this was a good argument for doing a stock buyba=
ck instead of a dividend. But if you are suspicious of stock buybacks, this=
 is a bad thing: This is just =E2=80=9Cstock buybacks let companies pay mon=
ey to shareholders without making them pay tax.=E2=80=9D You might want the=
m to pay tax!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cubHcuY29tL2FkbWluL3VwbG9hZC9TaXRlQXR0YWNobWVudHMvQWxlcnQlMjAzMDAx=
LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf411b382" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> imposes a 1% excise tax=
</a> on stock buybacks by public companies. The people who demanded that ta=
x probably dislike stock buybacks a lot more than I do, so in some theoreti=
cal sense I feel like I should disapprove of this tax. But on the other han=
d the excise tax just makes stock buybacks=C2=A0<em>slightly=C2=A0</em>less=
 tax efficient, putting them on closer to a level playing field with divide=
nds, and I guess that=E2=80=99s fine. I can=E2=80=99t get too worked up abo=
ut it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said there are some oddities. At Axios, <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29062030.270537/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tLzIwMjIvMDkvMTUvdGhlLW5ldy10YXgtb24tc3BhY3M/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB27777718" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Dan Primack reports</a>=C2=A0that the=
 1% tax =E2=80=9Ccould be applied to SPAC redemptions.=E2=80=9D The way a s=
pecial purpose acquisition company works is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A sponsor raises money by selling sto=
ck to the public at $10 per share.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>She puts the money in a pot and looks for an acquisition target.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If she finds one, the SPAC merges with the =
target. The target gets the money in the pot and becomes a public company; =
the shareholders of the SPAC get shares of the target.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If she does not find a target (or=
 the shareholders don=E2=80=99t approve the one she finds), which seems inc=
reasingly likely for a lot of SPACs these days, then the SPAC liquidates an=
d returns the money in the pot (plus a bit of interest) to shareholders.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is that a =E2=80=9Cstock buyback=E2=80=9D? Wel=
l, sure, I guess. People put money into the company, time passed, and the c=
ompany gave them the money back. The company tried to do something with the=
 money, but it failed, so it just returned it. And there=E2=80=99s a 1% tax=
 on the way out.</p>
